(from a [review comment|https://svn.atlassian.com/atlaseye/cru/CR-CONF-289/#c9327])

Selenium tests often need to run custom JavaScript code, but the calls usually involve priming jQuery to point to the RTE iframe's document and then several lines of escaped JavaScript in the Java classes.

For one test we needed code like:

{code:JavaScript}
putCursorAtPostionInElement : function (selector, position) {
        var ed = tinyMCE.activeEditor, doc = ed.getDoc();

        // need the #text node inside the selected element, so filter the child nodes of the selector
        var el = $(selector, doc).contents().filter(function(){ return this.nodeType == 3; })[0];
        var range = (this.IERange && this.IERange.createRange) ? this.IERange.createRange(doc) : doc.createRange();
        range.setStart(el, position);
        range.setEnd(el, position);
        ed.selection.setRng(range);
    }
{code}

which ended up being added to tinyMceAdapter.js. In this case we will probably get reuse from this code in production, but other test JS methods should _not_ go in the production scripts.

We need a way to make helper methods available to our Selenium tests, this would best be achieved with a Confluence plugin.

